name: sfchronicle
text:

text:

name: sfchronicle
text: Many restaurants in the Bay Area can offer only outdoor dining because of coronavirus restrictions. With temperatures dropping, restaurants are looking frantically for heat lamps — and having trouble finding them. https://t.co/iyik9PlINj

name: sfchronicle
text:
Coronavirus cases in San Francisco have tripled over the past four weeks, public health officials said.

The city has reported an average of 130 new cases a day this week, compared to 73 per day in the first week of November. https://t.co/5B4KhzK1Nb https://t.co/mz8gWq6Kt2

name: sfchronicle
text:
JUST IN: The nine Bay Area counties together reported 2,027 new coronavirus cases by Saturday afternoon — a new daily high for the region, according to data reported by county health departments and compiled by The Chronicle and the L.A. Times.

https://t.co/tG7r9uCI4C

text: Janet Yellen, President-elect Joe Biden’s expected nominee for Treasury secretary, would be the first woman to lead the department if confirmed, after breaking barriers as the first woman to chair the Federal Reserve from 2014 to 2018. https://t.co/e22QswvG4l

name: sfchronicle
text:
The U.S. recorded over 200,000 daily coronavirus cases for the first time on Saturday.

To put it in perspective, that’s about 6 in every 10,000 Americans recording a positive test.

https://t.co/4hj3XIXdg4

name: sfchronicle
text:
The country surpassed the 4 million mark for new cases in November on Saturday, more than doubling October's tally of 1.9 million cases, according to data collected by Johns Hopkins University. 

https://t.co/BMXEZVQ5Tu

name: sfchronicle
text: “The data are clear: the current surge of COVID-19 cases is more aggressive and widespread than we have previously experienced,” Dr. Grant Colfax, San Francisco’s director of health, said in a statement. “We must take decisive action now.” https://t.co/nUMPqYvVLV

name: sfchronicle
text:
Currently, no African Americans hold any key power positions with any of the Bay Area’s professional sports teams. 

Only Stanford has a Black person in the power seat, actually two: director Bernard Muir and head football coach David Shaw. https://t.co/5LiAkzHkeN

The Candelabra Tree, a Bay Area landmark, is an old redwood so named for the four huge stems that extend from a trunk that is 20 feet in diameter.
